===Etymology===
1712, from {{term|addle||[[urine]], [[liquid]] [[filth]]|lang=en}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|adela||[[mud]], [[mire]], liquid [[manure]]|lang=ang}}, cognate with {{etyl|gmq-osw|-}} {{term|adel||urine|lang=gmq-osw}}, {{etyl|gml|-}} {{term|adel|lang=gml}}, Dutch {{term|aal||[[puddle]]|lang=nl}}. Used in [[noun phrase]] ''addle egg'' (mid-13c.) "egg that does not [[hatch]], [[rotten]] egg," lit. "urine egg," a [[loan translation]] of {{etyl|la|-}} {{term|ovum urinum|lang=la}}, which is itself an [[erroneous]] loan translation of {{etyl|grc|-}} {{term|οὔριον ᾠόν|tr=ourion oon||putrid egg|lang=grc}}, lit. "[[wind]] egg," from {{term|οὔριος|tr=ourios||of the wind|lang=grc}} from {{term|οὖρος|tr=ouros||fair wind|lang=grc}} (confused by Roman writers with {{term|οὔριος|tr=ourios||of urine|lang=grc}} from {{term|οὖρον|tr=ouron||urine|lang=grc}}). Because of this usage, the noun in English was taken as an adj. from c. 1600, meaning "putrid," and thence given a [[figurative]] [[extension]] to "[[empty]], [[vain]], [[idle]]," also "confused, [[muddled]], [[unsound]]" (1706). The verb followed.<ref>{{R:Online Etymology Dictionary|addle}}</ref>

